        <body>
            <pb n="1R"/>
            <p rend="align(right)">
                <placeName>Charleston</placeName>
                <date>Sep 2d 1852</date>
            </p>
            <p>Dear <addressee>Mr Leeser</addressee></p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">Your esteemed favor is at hand. I enclose<lb/> the Original
                transcript of Laws &amp;c from which I selected<lb/> what I thought would answer—the
                numbers <del>you</del>
                <sic>refered</sic><lb/> to <persName>Maimonides</persName> Sanhedrin,
                    <persName>Pesek</persName> 18, all the numbers<lb/> refer to that section:—if
                you have the room it would<lb/> be as well to give the hebrew text as well. You
                can<lb/> arrange <add>these sent instead of what I copied</add> so as to read
                    sonvoltly<add>?</add>, The article will<lb/> not grow stale, as it will do good
                whenever I comes<lb/> you are mistaken about the accident not being Read<lb/>—the
                enlightened always read it and they are the<lb/> only persons to Divine benefit
                therefrom,</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">I send you also a communication for
                <persName>Breslaw</persName><lb/> I would have sent it direct, but I want you
                to<lb/> read it first and if it will benefit you, send it on<lb/> for publication in
                the asmoneon, if not publish<lb/> it in the Occident. do with it what you like, I
                have<lb/> used logical argument and not touched on the<lb/> subject of your dispute;
                let me know what you<lb/> think of it.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">I have no time to enlarge, but I must find<lb/> oppty to say at the
                request of <persName>Mrs Jacqueline Levy</persName><lb/> that she never made the
                remark alluded to about<lb/>
                <persName>Mr Jacob</persName>. She <add>?</add> that she never listened<lb/> to any
                discourse which touched her feelings as much<lb/> as yours.—but she feels proud that
                you think<lb/>
                <hi rend="underline">her opinion</hi> of sufficient consequence as to notice it.</p>
            <pb n="1V"/>
            <p>I delivered your note to <persName>N Levin</persName>, <hi rend="underline">all
                    right</hi></p>
            <p rend="indent(1)"><persName>Dr Eckman</persName> has recd an invitation from the<lb/>
                Congregation at Sarameat<add>?</add> to officiate for the<lb/> coming holidays,
                which he will accept<lb/> I saw <persName>Dr Myer</persName> and told him that you
                had not<lb/> heard from him about the article in <persName>Dr Phillipps</persName>
                packet<lb/> he had the impertinence to deny to me that he<lb/> told me he intended
                to write you, he turns it off<lb/> by saying if you had written him
                    <del>directly</del> personally he would<lb/> have replied.—he denies having
                written the article<lb/> I told him what I thought of him.—</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)"><persName>Mr Jacobs</persName> is daily expected</p>
            <p>Kind regards to all. Yours Truly</p>
            <p rend="indent(4)">
                <persName role="author">J N Carvalho</persName>
            </p>
        </body>
